comments.text:
jayztwocents please pin this comment. 
do not buy the 5090.  if you have one then ask for a refund.
5090 will be recalled.  
the 12v rails comming into the card are joined together and put through a single shunt resistor. 
there is zero load balancing.  and the wire can self ignite. 
it's litterally a fire hazard. 
if you cut 5 of the 6 12 wires.  the card will not even know that happend and pull 600 watts though the single remaining wire.  
this is enoegh power to make it glow. 

even on a fully functioning cable.  the current through a single wire can be 22 amps when the rest has 3-6 amps.  
the 5090 is a dangerous device that should not be bought untill this problem is fixed.  

again.  there is absolutely no load balancing on a 600 watts card.
comments.author: @darkracer1252

comments.text:
as a side note.   on the 4090's this is ALSO a problem.  and that is why the cable melted when a poor connection gave it a chance.  
there is no load balancing. it should stop functioning if one of the cables is broken.  not pull so much power through the remaining ones that they melt.
comments.author: @darkracer1252

comments.text:
For a GPU to render/draw the "3 Fake Frames in between", it must already know what the "Next Real Frame" looks like.
This is the real issue!
So for a Game being Faked into 4x fps, the GPU has to hold back the next frame that it already knows about to be able to draw the next 3 fake frames.
Consider 6fps raw, 1/60th of a second it holds that next frame back, it is adding 16.66 ms of latency to every rendered frame.

This would easily be seen on camera. Why is no one demonstrating this!

comments.text:
People who think that the DLSS causes more latency don't understand DLSS. All it's doing is adding frames in between the input frames or the frame set can react to input by the user It does not slow down the rastered frames It only adds interpolated frames between them. You are getting more frames between input/rastered frames but the frames are occurring at a much faster rate.
For example if you are running a game with 60 FPS with DLSS turned off and then you turn it on and you get 120 frames per second You are still getting the 60 rested frames per second and adding one interpolated frame between each one so you're latency is exactly the same in each case.😮

comments.text:
At least the biggest thing Jay makes very clear in this review is that the 5090 is not meant to be an everyday gamers GPU. It is meant to be the kind of do everything card, with heavy focus on production/AI. It amazes me how many will talk about an xx90 card like it is the peak of gaming, but if you ever ask if they do anything else with it they look utterly confused/lost as to what you mean.

I've turned down doing builds for people (a side thing I do) simply because they insist on a xx90 card but only plan to game with it. Got tired of trying to not just save them money on something they don't need, but being in a spot where they will take a significant loss when the next big xx90 card comes out - especially since Nvidia keeps locking very specific software to newer models which in essence drives their 'performance' so much higher.

The other concern with this card too, is how it can heat soak a closed case with restrictive air flow. Don't get me wrong, the cooler does a surprising job at cooling a 600w card, but the amount of heat it blows out under load will quickly saturate the inside of a case affecting poor flow cases, air cooled CPU, and even water loops depending on how you have them set up a good deal. Just hoping the rest of the line doesn't have similar issues as this gives me vibes of the Fermi days where those cards ran hot as all get out.

comments.text:
By using the integrated GPU to handle tasks like frame output to the monitor, the dedicated GPU was free to focus solely on rendering the game.
This reduced the load on the PCIe bus and sped up frame delivery, resulting in lower input lag and potentially smoother performance.
The iGPU would act as a "frame limiter," ensuring only frames that the monitor could display were sent, avoiding redundant frame rendering.  The iGPU (Intel HD Graphics 3000) essentially acted as a "traffic manager," taking care of passing frames to the monitor.
This allowed the dedicated GPU to avoid the overhead of rendering frames that might not even be displayed, resulting in quicker frame delivery and smoother gameplay.
Avoiding Redundant Frame Rendering

Instead of pushing out as many frames as possible (some of which might exceed your monitor's refresh rate and be wasted), the iGPU ensured only the necessary frames were passed to the display.
This not only reduced input lag but also prevented unnecessary workload on the dedicated GPU, keeping it focused on rendering high-quality frames.
Smoother Gameplay Without Excessive Frames

Lucid Virtu was a victim of its time and the competitive nature of the tech industry. The idea was revolutionary, but it relied on cooperation between competing giants like Intel, NVIDIA, and AMD. That kind of collaboration isn’t easy, especially when everyone is trying to dominate their piece of the market. Here's why it probably fell apart:   Now NVIDIA is inserting frames with AI to boost FPS. Come on, guys, focus on quality, not quantity!

comments.text: something notable with all these high power builds. power supply efficiency is going to play a big role in keeping your room from turning into as much of an oven. if the power supply vents into your case. a 90% efficient power supply will dump almost 100W of heat into your case/room. an under desk space heater is 200W for reference. total system power being 900w (with only a 90% power supply) is actually a space heater in your room. in summer. door closed. these things are getting so power hungry that they nearly need a dedicated circuit breaker. most people wont be able to add an window AC to their rooms because one CB is not enough for that pc and an AC unit. most houses don't even use a dedicated CB for each room. its pretty common for multiple bedrooms to share a single breaker. usb and video over fiber and Ethernet is looking better and better for these power hungry builds so you can keep the PC with loud fans and heat in the basement or whatever.

comments.text: The upside with buying a 50 series card is that you still have the choice as to whether you want to run frame gen or not. In anything that requires responsive controls (especially online FPS), I think it's best left off. Until Nvidia breaks the laws of physics, by using AI to predict when a player is going to peek an angle, frame-gen will just be a novel motion-smoothing feature for more casual titles. Until frame gen becomes the standard, bare-metal performance benchmarks will always be best practice! If that happens though, output FPS will unfortunately become less and less relevant (similar to how CPU clock-speeds are only tangentially linked to performance), making it increasingly more difficult for us to truly assess a card's performance. Thanks for the review!

comments.text:
So I stopped at 16:00 to write this

What you see and feel is the AI frames. The programs that read FPS probably have a 'limit' of sorts when reading the frames but still read the avg frames. To put it simply it can't read the low frames properly and reads what the game is putting out. This could factor in the abnormal reading. 

As for the weird 'it feels like a 60fps and not a 200fps', what you feel is the fake frames. What I mean with fake frames is a copy of the current frame and the next ones trying to predict what comes next. It might look awesome but it won't feel the same as the your input won't be in those frames, only what the current frame shows would be taken to the next AI frames, hence the input lag since your input can't be generated in the AI frames.

comments.text:
First and foremost, congratulations JTC team. This presentation is neat and informative. There is significant improvement. I like your personal feedback regarding the pwr connection.

Regarding frame gen technology, the proper way to use the 4x frame to achive optimum smoothness and input latency is by capping the frame produce in game.

Let say you have a 240Hz, 4k monitor. You play Cyberpunk 2077 with medium ray tracing like in that graf. Locking the frame to 60fps and enabling 4x frame gen will let you play with optimal input latency and smoothness of 240fps, the limit of your monitor. The gpu will have some computing headroom from reducing the load on resterising images. The  spare computing capability can reduce power usage and  generating less heat. It will then be use to assist the software part to generate constant 240 fps throught the game play.

The image quality of the generated image is a different topic that can be test and discuse later.

14:48 I FUCKING KNEW IT! The moment I saw that the 50 series was getting stupid amount of frames and it was based on multi frame generation, I knew there would be the latency issue. 
It's a gimmick, and not a good one. There's a program(Lossless Scaling - its on steam) that simulates frame generation and multi frame generation on games that don't support it. I've tried it and it's had 3x frame gen for a while. The latency was massive, but considering the card I used was a 30 series, I was surprised it worked at all. lol. 30 fps on the 3x becomes 90 fps, but for every real frame lost, you lose 3.. The frames gain isn't worth the latency - in my experience. A friend that has a 40 series says it works well, but the 3 or 4x frame gen adds way to much latency still.

If AMD wants to win this generation, they will have to get close to the same frames as the MFG Nvidia cards without the gimmick. Pure, real frames. AI ain't it.

comments.text:
Jay, the reason you can't use Elmor's PCIe adapter to measure the power consumption of the PCIe slot is because Nvidia doesn't use a DIRECT PCIe connection to the motherboard with the FE, but because of the fans blowing through the card design, Nvidia already installed a riser cable on the FE card from the factory! Technically speaking, Elmor's adapter is riser no. 2, which is why the signal integrity of PCIe 5.0 is lost because the voltages that are absolutely necessary for PCIE 5.0 drop too much because each plug contact means an additional transition resistance! Switch PCIe back to 4.0 in the BIOS and you will see that Elmor's adapter works again (and also the 5090 FE) because the voltage tolerances under PCIe 4.0 don't have to be so high.

Use a different 5090 from a board partner and you will see that Elmor's adapter suddenly works again despite PCIe 5.0. So, as you said in the video, it's not because Elmor's adapter still has PCIe 4.0 and/or is incompatible, but because the voltages required for PCIe 5.0 simply drop too much with 2 adapters.

In the future, these types of problems will become more and more common because the technology only uses faster connections, which means that every detour via adapters and extensions represents a hurdle that is not only measurably worse, but will completely disable the function itself. Because it prevents signal integrity.

EDIT: OHH and I forgot...If you plan on using the FE with a typical riser cable (even if it says 5.0!) for STANDING installation in a typical fish tank case like the Lian Li O11 Dynamic etc., FORGET THAT, it won't work for the same reason mentioned before! DO NOT buy a 5090 FE for standing installation via a RISER cable! Buy a 5090 Boardpartner card for it! The same applies of course to EVERYONE who uses water cooling and wants to put the 5090 under water...

comments.text:
@Nareimooncatt  Even if you use all the fan slots, the Y60/Y70 is significantly worse in terms of cooling than other cases with the same hardware. There are enough tests online that prove this. The problem here is the paneling of the case on the top/bottom and the right-hand side, which is not made of MESH all the way round but of this very wide line design that is supposed to create a cool look but which unnecessarily blocks the air! The air filters are also located inside in front of it. The wide line design alone blocks 50% of the area + where the air filter grille does not run over the lines but over the still free area. That's why the temperatures are higher. Not critical yet, but higher. Trying to defend this case that you have because it "works" for you with relatively frugal hardware plays no role here.

Many will compensate for this by using higher fan speeds (especially in summer). I just don't want to have to play with headphones just because in the summer the case on top of the desk next to me turns into a vacuum cleaner... because the mainboard increases the speed the hotter it is outside. And that inevitably happens the warmer it gets at your place. Even with a 4070TI / 4080 / 4090 that "only" consumes up to 450 watts. What do you think happens with a 5090 card that emits 600 watts (and more as tests have shown!) in heat in your case!? Then you no longer have a vacuum cleaner, it becomes a screaming HAIRDRYER that tries to force the air through these "optically stylish" case slats!

@Jay Just saw the review video from Igor's Lab. The problem probably is not the adapter form Elmor's Lab, but that the adapter is basically a second riser.
Igor's Lab saw that the FE cards don't work with risers, he checked several computers. And the reason is simple: Nvidia has to use a cable connecting the GPU to the slot. comments.text:
Taking a over the top $2000 card, and only doing one benchmark with it's flagship feature (Multi-Frame Gen), on medium Ray tracing, not even bothering to max it out to path tracing, and ZERO DLSS upscaling benchmarks feels like some kinda crime of omission. You can't accuse nvidia of biases and marketing gimmicks when you're basically doing the same thing on the other end of the spectrum. It's an unbalanced viewpoint and misrepresents the reality and use cases of these cards.

Rasterization performance improvements are nearing their end of the life. AI Image generation is the future of this card and it really needs to be given more weight, especially considering that most people can't even tell the difference outside of twitch reliant gameplay (FPS esports).

It's sad to see you lean in the direction of Gamers Nexus on this stuff, rather than Digital Foundry. I know you'll adjust course in time (cause you'll have to), but consider doing a deep dive comparison of the DLSS performance generation over generation, and exploring the different settings there. Most of the titles DLSS won't work with, are likely going to be old enough that turning on these features isn't necessary any way, so the only reason someone is gonna plop down $2k on this thing is because they want to run the latest titles with full ray/path tracing at ultra settings in 4k. And you're gonna get 30fps without DLSS, so why bother with a 5090 in the first place if not for DLSS?

comments.text:
I greatly appreciate the benchmark and review videos for information like this. Great video.

Even though we can pause the vid & go back to see the charts, I do think there was plenty of time to extend the duration they stayed up on screen. IMO, I'd rather not have to pause or go back to see things while I'm going thru my initial viewing of the video. Yeah, I'm lazy, but pausing or going back interrupts the flow of the video and it's just my personal preference to not have to (& I'm sure other's would agree.)

I also would argue that the dB of the cooler's fans is still relevant, especially when optimizing our rigs for performance; however, I do agree that pitch or frequency that the fans are generating is also equally as important. I say this because 65dB noise, regardless of pitch, is still equivalent to someone yelling. Granted your [generally speaking] room's noise floor makes a huge difference here, but most rooms are going to be between high 30s to mid 40s in dB, which will be very quiet measurably, but more importantly perceptively, when comparing to my above example of 65dB. Pitch/freqs generated will determine how annoying said noise will be, generally higher pitched noises are more strenuous on an individual's ears & cause listening fatigue sooner. If I was to get the 5090 at all, I would greatly prefer it over the 4090 FE card for multiple reasons, but the difference in the noise generated by the cooler would be more acceptable due to the lower pitch IMO.

comments.text: I like that you bring up ray tracing and how at first people thought it was a gimmick, but now every title has it. Especially considering that, as a whole, the way the industry is going since live calculated ray tracing and the associated technologies being developed to help games with these newer technologies run efficiently has been an overall negative. I was playing Alien Isolation the other day because I never beat it when I bought it and wanted to play something with good graphics, and I was absolutely floored at how well it holds up graphically. The game was made in 2014 and it looks better than the new Resident Evil remakes if you reduce their graphics quality to remove all the showy new technologies. It's all well thought out light mapping, well thought out shaders and materials, with the sole purpose of looking realistic. Let's not forget that Unreal Engine is developed with Fortnite in mind, and then people go and try to make something realistic with the technologies Epic is developing to produce faux-realism, that are designed with a specific stylistic look in mind. People see the tech demos, using meticulously configured settings to get a realistic look, and then think they can just get away with throwing things at the closed box expecting them to find their own way in. This will be another stain Nvidia unleashes on the community, and eventually people will just put up with it because that's how it is now, and if everyone is playing with the same input delay then technically it's still competitive, right? While all of us who grew up in the time before can be like "Back in my day, when you gave the game an input, it responded immediately!" Okay grandpa, sit down. No one cares about your ridiculous exaggerations about the war on technology.

comments.text:
With the latest Cyberpunk update, the DLSS version has been upgraded to 310.1.0.0 (nvngx_dlss.dll). By copying this DLL file into the folder where any DLSS-supported game’s executable file is located, we might be able to use the latest DLSS version across all games. However, the DLSS Swapper program hasn’t received an update yet.

In Cyberpunk 2077, we can now switch the DLSS model from the old CNN-based method to the new Transformer model. If this model switch is necessary, developers should consider adding this option to all DLSS-supported games in the future.

On another note, the ghosting issue (trailing effects on moving objects) has been significantly reduced, which is great news. As an RTX 4080 user, the best part of the RTX 5000 series is that we’ll also benefit from DLSS 4. For those using RTX 3000 cards, keep an eye on updates—there are rumors that NVIDIA might bring Frame Generation to the RTX 3000 series as well.

comments.text:
@JayzTwoCents regarding presentmon, I would investigate if you see FPS drops like I did with the presentmon overlay active, it seems to take performance away which OSDs like Rivatuner don't.

In Sniper Elite 5 main menu where I got 150fps at 1440p ultra on the 1080Ti, it would sometimes drop below 140fps with Intel PresentMon active and keep varying a lot in framerate.

In Batman Arkham Knight I even saw a drop from 130-140fps to 82fps on the 1080Ti in a specific spot with the presentmon overlay active at game boot, after an alt-tab the FPS mostly restored but there was still a dip in framerate.

During the alt-tab the overlay is also seen on the desktop instead of only the game, hinting to me that it's a borderless window that just draws 'on-top' of other programs in fullscreen which is causing issues for the framerate consistency. 

What extra empowers this fact is that the built-in G-sync framecounter of my Asus PG279Q Monitor ceases to function when the PresentMon overlay is active in a game indicating it is taking something over from the rendering pipeline in the wrong way.

I think PresentMon needs work to be actually useable as a proper method of testing, Fraps with FRAFS benchviewer do not exhibit but unfortunately don't support modern APIs and Rivatuner benchmark doesn't show you the 99th or 95th percentiles and neither a recorded .csv export with the frametimes for each frame.

So... yeah...

comments.text:
The 5090 is only 32% faster than the 4090 in gaming; and as Jay says this card has a lot do benefits outside of game, which makes sense because the 4090/5090 should not be purchased for just a gaming rig!!!

My 4080 can run Indiana jones with everything maxed out DLSS performance with NO frame gen getting 60-70fps. 

As of right now, frame gen is not needed, and with a 5080 it will be needed even less; unless Nvidia programs the drivers to specify hinder performance (like it seems to be with DLSS) to require frame gen. This is very possible in the next couple of years; but the problem with this is like 2025 games like Indian jibes requiring GpUs with RT cores making cards that are over 6 years old (GTX 1000) obsolete. If newer games in the future start requiring multiple frame gen, RTX 4000 and older will become obsolete! I doubt the will happen in 2 years, but could happen in 4 years making the 4,000 series 6 years old at that time requiring everyone to upgrade to at least a 5,000 series. This can only happen though if the demands of future games require the use of multiframe gen; which means AMD and Intel would have to develop their own multiframe gen tech. My guess is if it comes down to this, AMD and Intel may just not bother making GPU’s anymore; given only nvidia makes a high end GPU I could see this happening.

Yeah bigger number better syndrome, the better your base real, raster, frame draw, the better it will feel, so it's a challenge for Nvidia at this point but could change somehow or get worse, who knows, that is the future and unlike leakers and those that spread rumors, I don't have a crystal ball.
From the 3 or 4 testing I have watched this card is a bit of a head scratcher, again I can't tell the future, but DLSS 4 , noise, granted in a case it might be less but what I've seen is yeps it be loud but it's a 2 slot card, absolutely wild the heat this thing is throwing off it, I'm curious to see what case manufacturers will do to try to cool the memory or VRMS? That's where it's hot spot.
 seems to be showing.
Oh and as far as price? Nope unless you game at 4 to 8 k skip this card, now if you want to work at home but have a 4090? Skip this card if you got the cash and have fomo? Fine buy it there's some cool little tools under the hood that gamers will never find value in but others might.
If you want to game at 1440 or 1080, nope waste of money but AMD, or if you go a fairly good updated system then buy Intel. Come on folks be real I counted at least 5 channels that had someone from Intel say the B series was a forward facing card and used technology that on older systems won't run as well, so when the cards came out and some of these same channels acted like it was a surprise more than just something that Intel needs to be better at next time or even correct in future cards of the B line .
I wish it was not as limiting as it is but it's not like it was unexpected.
Bottom line 5090 yeah kinda a head scratcher, not a bad card, but not a casual gamer card by any means, but if you work at home be it for fun or as serious as making your own game this is your latest probably best offer, oh don't forget movie editing.
It's also your most expensive offer, with everything under it starting with the 5080 being cut down, the 80 card is pretty much cut by half in all ways as far as price and performance, this alone gives me the meh vibes all over again, but it's up to the individual buyer, the new software solutions might be enough to push some over the edge and buy a 80 though I seriously would wait to see 3rd party testing.

comments.text:
I have a potentially strange question.
What actually happens if you cap your FPS at 120 but have Frame Generation enabled? If it's a 1:1 ratio, does the game run at 60 FPS and "generate" the other 60 to reach 120? Or will it "drop" generated frames if the card is rendering, say, 90 FPS? (So you render 90 real frames and add 30 generated frames to hit 120.) Or will it drop "real frames" for generated one?

If this technology could be used to "smooth out" FPS drops, it could actually be quite nice.

Damn, if I think about it, in the first case you would save a lot of energy costs, and in the second case, you could use a 3:1 ratio just to always hit 120 FPS, even if you're only getting between 30 and 60 FPS while playing. Smoothing out FPS drops like that would be awesome!

Could you test this, @jayztwocents?

And yes, I know input lag is a thing. But if the game renders at around 60 FPS, it's good enough for every non-hardcore competitive game. There are plenty of games out there besides shooters where FPS doesn't really matter as much.

i am kind of surprised the raster performance improvement was so meh.
i did kind of expect a ~50% improvement from the 4090 to the 5090, and the more modest ~25-30% performance improvement in the other models.
But if the raster performance improvement is so modest in this card, then i can only expect the raster performance improvement in the other models to be even more modest, say 15-20%
in this way the 5080 wouldn't catch the 4090 and the 5070 would barely reach the 4070 ti in raster performance.

not to say this or the other models would be "bad", the new multi gen frame generation tech on these cards looks powerful, but the raster performance improvement is fairly mediocre, which render the infamous "5070=4090" claim even closer to outright false advertising.

i was kind of expecting better ray tracing improvements too...

My rtx 4090 (asus gaming oc 4-slot) runs at nearly 3000mhz frequency out of the box. It also rarely goes above 400w and never 450w. Including furmark which tops out at 410w and frequency drops only a little to 2880mhz core and max temp of 64c.

When comparing against all the benchmarks my 4090 gets on average 17% higher scores at 4k vs other 4090s.

So, with almost 200w less power it is only maxed 20% slower than the 5090 but average of 12%.

With AIO board partners not using liquid metal and using similar cooling as the 4090 the actual improvements might be less than  10%. Plus the extra heat is significant and has to go somewhere. Meaning ram, cpu and nvme hard drive temps will certainly suffer.

Yeh, I won't be selling for a rtx 5070 lol although, the 5090 FE cooler is pretty rad

comments.text:
Wouldn't it be better if the GPU rendered the game "without any graphics" (like just the meshes, engine, and physics things) and then used the "fake frames" to essentially colour these scenes in, the latency issue would go away? 

If you can get the GPU with AI elements to run at a Frame Gen Per Second (FGPS, lets makes it happen) of 200, running at a raster FPS of 50, why not render the FGPS at a base of 40 FPS, giving a FGPS of 120, and run the game engine without any rasterization at a higher FPS than the raster output as close to the FGPS as possible?

Hoping that makes some sort of sense, and that we see new engines developed to leverage this potential power sitting in the 5000 series.

TLDR; Could developers make an engine that runs at 4x the speed of the "fps output" of a games output to remove as much latency as possible. Generated frames would be overlaid with the actual input to output speed of the games engine

comments.text: 1kw PSUs have been around for a decade at this point. I've had one for 8 years now. Optimal PSU efficiency is running at 50% load.
comments.author: @TopShot501st

comments.text:
​ @TopShot501st , true.  Same here.  Now, an existing 1kw psu is not going to run at 50% load, but more like at 80-100%.  To maintain 50% load, we'll be talking about a 1.8-2.0 kw psu.

Jumping off of that, the psu capacity wouldn't be the concern, the actual power drawn during intended use will be.

Short of a significant architectural change, I'm expecting power draw to just increase as performance increase.  Ex. intel throwing power at its typical CPU layout vs AMD and x3D with its comparable performance at lower power usage.

Maybe one day we'll find a scaling law for performance vs power usage, similar to neural scaling laws we're seeing for machine learning models.  Perhaps finding such a scaling law that is agnostic to any gpu architecture you throw at it will finally kill all hopes of better or same power efficiency while increasing or maintaining performance.  Until then though...

comments.text: According to Nvidia AI guy 40 series frame gen was a hardware feature reliant on hardware optical flow accelerator. But 50 series multi frame gen is actually a software feature running a visual transformer model and tensor based optical flow algorithm on tensor cores. So It could be run even on 30 series. The question is does those older cards have enough compute power to handle increased load. That fact makes me skeptical for transformer DLSS being viable on 30 and 20 series cause TOPS power is not there even on most powerful cards.

comments.text:
@Daisudori  you don't need that. 
you can just roast marshmellows on the fire it creates. 
(no joke this is a PSA) 
the 5090 is a fire hazard.  
6 12v rails comming into a single rail with a single shunt resistor.  

no load balancing means if you cut 5 of the six wires it will not know it happened and happely pull 600 watts through a single wire.  
even on a fully intact cable the load diffrence can be as much as for example 22 amps through a single wire. (heating it up to 150 celcius after a while on full load) 
while 3-6 amps are going through the others. (because it's impossible to get the same exact resistance across these wires)

there's a few video's on this subject out there.  i recommend watching them. and then wait for the nvidia recall of the 5090's

Lets take CP2077 case - 4090, natively (no dlss or FG, path tracing on, maxed out settings) had 20fps avg. 5090 has 33fps. 6090 probably gonna have like 47-50fps (coming in 2027+) and 7090 is the gpu that could actually keep over 60fps in 4k, without any upscallers and tricks in... 2030!. 

I seen irl what 50 series cards can do with the DLSS4 and the 4xFG, and I am fine with the results. I was about to get 5090, but the Gigabyte one draws over 800W in the peak x.x Sorry, but I won't be paying 0.3€ for every hour of my gameplay. I will be preordering 5080, which is like 15% stronger than 4080 by math, and over 100% stronger by AI upscaling. Powerdraw is similar to 7900xtx.
